    "plan": "# Plan — v2 graph benchmark fixtures\n\n## Ordering rationale\n\nFixture design is cheap to get wrong and expensive to re-benchmark, so this plan front-loads **outline → validate → implement** rather than jumping straight to YAML. The cheapest step (outline in markdown) exposes whether the fixture is well-defined; the next-cheapest step (naive-grep counter-check) catches false-positive fixtures before any sweep runs.\n\nEach candidate fixture passes through three gates before landing:\n\n1. **Gate A — outlined.** Has a clear prompt, ground truth, and hypothesized grep failure mode.\n2. **Gate B — grep-falsified.** Running the naive grep pattern at the pinned SHA demonstrably produces an answer that fails the oracle (either hits `must_not_include` or misses `must_include`).\n3. **Gate C — graph-passable.** At least one provider passes under `graph-only` at seed 1. If no provider passes, the fixture goes back to Gate A.\n\n## Step 1 — Establish working directory and SHA pin\n\n- Confirm the current living-harness SHA: `git rev-parse HEAD` at repo root. Pin this SHA in every new fixture's `commit_sha` field.\n- Create `benchmarks/graph/V2_FIXTURES.md` as an empty scaffold with sections for each candidate fixture (populated in Step 2).\n- Read `benchmarks/graph/tasks/_schema.yaml` and `benchmarks/graph/tasks/trace-policy-denial-wiring.yaml` end-to-end as templates; all new fixtures must match that shape.\n\n## Step 2 — Outline 6 candidate fixtures (target 4 landed)\n\nAuthor 6 candidates to account for attrition at Gates B and C. One per category, plus 2 spares.\n\nFor each candidate, write a section in `V2_FIXTURES.md` with:\n\n- **Task ID** (kebab-case).\n- **Class** (one of `locate | trace | impact | deps`).\n- **Naive grep pattern** — the exact `rg` invocation an agent would reach for first.\n- **Expected grep failure mode** — why the output is wrong or ambiguous. Specific and verifiable.\n- **Ground truth** — the exact set of paths/symbols the agent must list. Hand-curated from the repo at the pinned SHA.\n- **Graph-tool path** — which `orbit.graph.*` tool(s) resolve the ambiguity, and in what sequence.\n\n### Candidate pool (6 to draft, 4+ to land)\n\n1. **`locate-runtime-name-collision`** (locate) — Two traits with the short name `Runtime` exist in different crates. Ask for the trait used by a specific caller. Grep `trait Runtime` returns both; the graph distinguishes via typed edges.\n\n2. **`callers-transitive-policy-check`** (trace) — \"List every function that transitively calls `OrbitPolicy::check_read` within 3 hops, across crates.\" Grep can name direct callers only; `orbit.graph.callers` walks the edge graph structurally.\n\n3. **`trace-audit-event-construct-multi-variant`** (trace) — Stronger version of `trace-policy-denial-wiring`. Pick `LoopAuditEvent` (has ~8 variants); ask for construct-sites on a specific 3-variant subset. Grep on variant names returns construct + pattern sites intermixed.\n\n4. **`impact-rename-tool-context-field`** (impact) — \"If the field `X` on `ToolContext` is renamed, which files need changes?\" Must include struct-literal constructions, dotted reads, `TypeName { X, .. }` patterns. Grep on the bare field name returns false positives from unrelated types with the same field.\n\n5. **`deps-reverse-dependents-orbit-common`** (deps) — \"Which crates reverse-depend on `orbit-common`?\" Grep on `orbit-common` in Cargo.toml files works, but misses the distinction between `path =` and `version =` deps, and doesn't include dev/build dependency edges. The graph answers this directly.\n\n6. **`locate-impl-under-generic-constraint`** (locate) — A trait with impls that are `impl<T: Bound> Trait for Foo<T>`. Grep `impl Trait for Foo` misses the generic forms. Spare candidate — prioritize landing if one of 1–5 fails Gate B.\n\nPick 4 to carry forward after Step 3.\n\n## Step 3 — Gate B: naive-grep counter-check\n\nFor each candidate from Step 2, at the pinned SHA:\n\n- Run the documented naive `rg` pattern against the repo.\n- Record the top 10 hits verbatim in the candidate's `V2_FIXTURES.md` section.\n- Compare against the hand-curated ground truth. Confirm **at least one** of:\n  - A `must_not_include` path appears in the grep output (false positive), OR\n  - A `must_include` path is absent from the grep output (false negative).\n\nIf neither, the fixture is not grep-hard — drop it. Move to a spare.\n\n**Output of this step:** a reduced list of 4–5 fixtures that are provably grep-hard.\n\n## Step 4 — Write YAML fixtures\n\nFor each surviving fixture, author `benchmarks/graph/tasks/<task_id>.yaml` matching `_schema.yaml`:\n\n- `task_id`: kebab-case, matches filename.\n- `class`: from `{locate, trace, impact, deps}`. Ensure the final set covers ≥2 distinct classes (AC#8).\n- `difficulty`: `medium` or `hard` (v2 should push harder than v1's easy-leaning set).\n- `commit_sha`: the SHA pinned in Step 1.\n- `prompt`: verbatim user message. Be explicit about output format (path lists, counts, etc.) — follow `trace-policy-denial-wiring.yaml` as the style template.\n- `oracle.grep`:\n  - `must_include`: the hand-curated ground-truth paths/tokens.\n  - `must_not_include`: the top 3+ grep false positives identified in Step 3 (this is what makes the oracle rigorous — AC#3).\n\n## Step 5 — Gate C: graph-only smoke test\n\nFor each fixture, run:\n\n```\nbenchmarks/graph/scripts/run.sh graph-only <task_id> 1 --provider claude\nbenchmarks/graph/scripts/run.sh graph-only <task_id> 1 --provider codex\n```\n\nCheck `benchmarks/graph/runs/<provider>/graph-only/<task_id>/1.json` for `verdict: pass`.\n\n- If at least one provider passes: fixture lands.\n- If neither provider passes: add a `status: needs-refinement` note to the fixture's `V2_FIXTURES.md` entry and move to the next spare. Do not land a fixture that no provider can solve — that's a harness problem, not a measurement.\n\nThis step is a one-shot check at seed 1, not a full 5-seed sweep. The full sweep is the separate follow-up task.\n\n## Step 6 — Update `V2_FIXTURES.md` with final shape\n\nFor each landed fixture, record in `V2_FIXTURES.md`:\n\n- (a) the naive grep pattern\n- (b) why it fails (concrete, not abstract)\n- (c) which graph tool(s) resolve it\n- (d) the Gate B counter-check result (grep output vs. ground truth)\n- (e) the Gate C smoke test result (claude pass / codex pass / both / one)\n\nThis satisfies AC#4 and AC#5 in one document.\n\n## Step 7 — Update `benchmarks/graph/README.md`\n\nAdd a `§Tasks` reference to `V2_FIXTURES.md`:\n\n> The v2 fixture set (additions since `graph_v1/`) is documented in [`V2_FIXTURES.md`](./V2_FIXTURES.md), including the grep-failure rationale for each new fixture.\n\nThis satisfies AC#10.\n\n## Step 8 — Final checks\n\n- Confirm `git diff benchmarks/graph_v1/` is empty (AC#7).\n- Confirm `git diff benchmarks/CONVENTIONS.md` is empty (AC#9).\n- Count landed fixtures: ≥4 (AC#1).\n- Count distinct classes across landed fixtures: ≥2 (AC#8).\n- Every landed YAML validates against `_schema.yaml` (AC#2) — spot-check by opening each file.\n- Every landed fixture's `must_not_include` has ≥3 entries corresponding to real grep false positives from Step 3 (AC#3).\n\n## Risks and mitigations\n\n- **Ground-truth drift mid-task.** The living workspace may move while this task is open, changing grep output or oracle truth. Mitigation: pin the SHA in Step 1 and re-check it before Step 5; if the repo has moved, re-run Gate B.\n- **A candidate looks grep-hard but Codex/Claude just grep-solve-it-anyway via cleverness.** This is the most likely failure mode. Mitigation: the `must_not_include` list must be tight enough that a grep agent's most natural path hits one of them. If Codex passes a \"grep-hard\" fixture with a single `rg` call, the fixture is not actually grep-hard — drop it.\n- **Overfitting to current implementations.** If a fixture is authored against the v1 repo shape and a refactor changes the ground truth, the fixture rots. Mitigation: the pinned `commit_sha` makes this explicit and auditable; future re-validations can re-pin.\n- **Fixture count inflation.** Don't add more than ~6 new fixtures to v2. Each fixture adds ~5–10 minutes per seed per arm per provider, and sweep cost multiplies fast. If the pool shrinks below 4 after Gates B + C, file a follow-up rather than landing weak fixtures.\n\n## Explicitly deferred\n\n- Running the full v2 sweep (separate follow-up).\n- Adding tool-utilization columns to `aggregate.py` (separate follow-up — v1 RESULTS.md recommendation #5).\n- Modifying any file under `benchmarks/graph_v1/`.\n- Modifying `benchmarks/graph/tasks/_schema.yaml`.\n- Authoring judge-based oracles; all v2 oracles use the `grep` form for parity with v1.",
