    "description": "## Problem\n\nWe have no repeatable way to measure whether `orbit.graph.*` tools actually reduce token usage for agents navigating the repo, and whether a hybrid arm beats either extreme. Design has been committed under `benchmarks/graph/README.md`; harness + fixtures do not yet exist.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nGraph value is currently argued from intuition. A fixed, reproducible benchmark lets us (a) justify the crate to skeptics with a number, (b) catch regressions when the graph extractor or pack format changes, (c) compare models and arms on the same yardstick.\n\n## Scope\n\nAll work lives under `benchmarks/graph/`. Three arms are already defined as Claude Code settings fragments in `benchmarks/graph/arms/{no-graph,graph-only,hybrid}.json`. Fixture schema is stubbed at `benchmarks/graph/tasks/_schema.yaml`.\n\nRemaining work:\n\n1. **Fixtures** — author ~18 task YAMLs across 3 classes (locate / trace / edit) x 3 tiers.\n2. **Run driver** — `benchmarks/graph/scripts/run.sh` that spawns a child Claude Code session with deterministic arm enforcement and captures token accounting.\n3. **LLM judge** — `scripts/judge.py` for open-ended fixtures.\n4. **Aggregator** — `scripts/aggregate.py` producing the headline table and a per-model breakdown.\n5. **Initial sweep** — `N=5` per cell, summary committed under `benchmarks/graph/results/<date>-summary.md`.\n\n## Constraints / Notes\n\n- Same model + version across any single sweep; `temperature=0`; fixed system prompt.\n- Fresh sandbox per run, no implicit state from prior runs.\n- `runs/` is gitignored; only summary markdown and fixture YAMLs are committed.\n- Judge model must differ from the run-under-test model.\n\n## Amendments — 2026-04-22 (from sanity-check runs 1 and 2)\n\nTwo single-fixture dry-runs on `locate AgentRuntime` exposed harness preconditions that must be baked into `run.sh` before any sweep. Evidence under `benchmarks/graph/runs/graph-only/locate-agentruntime/{1,2}.raw.json`.\n\n**Findings:**\n\n- Run 1 (no explicit `--mcp-config`) → the child `claude -p` inherited no MCP server from the parent and reported `permission_denials: []` while the agent wrote *I cant execute these tools*. The failure silently looked like a graph-arm loss when it was actually a harness bug. `~/.claude.json`s `mcpServers.orbit` entry is stale (`orbit mcp start` was renamed to `orbit serve mcp`); `claude mcp list` confirms the legacy command fails to connect.\n- Run 2 (with `--mcp-config /tmp/orbit-bench-mcp.json --strict-mcp-config`) → the agent answered correctly via MCP-only. Tool-name prefix in the child was `mcp__orbit__*`, not the parents `mcp__plugin_orbit_orbit__*`. Arm allowlists MUST use the prefix matching whichever MCP server name the bench config declares; the current `arms/*.json` files use the parents plugin prefix and will produce wrong results unless rewritten or overridden.\n- Both runs `modelUsage` maps list three models simultaneously (`claude-sonnet-4-6`, `claude-haiku-4-5-20251001`, `claude-opus-4-7`). This is Claude Codes internal routing — advisor, subagents, tool orchestration — not model escalation. A single `input_tokens + output_tokens` headline hides the mix. Per-model breakdown is required for honest reporting.\n- `permission_denials: []` + zero graph-tool calls in a graph-enabled arm is the signature of *arm not enforced*. That is not the same as *agent tried and failed*. The run-driver must distinguish them and emit `verdict: error` for the former.\n\nSee also friction task T20260422-1614 (`orbit.graph.pack` MCP schema drift) and feature T20260422-1621 (ship Claude Code permission bundle). The bundle task should additionally repair the stale `~/.claude.json` mcpServers entry.",
