    "description": "## Problem\n\nT20260421-0528 ships `task_ids` on graph nodes with an identity-only lineage matcher (match on `(path, qualified_name, [kind])`). Symbols that are renamed, moved across files, or extracted without a predecessor under those rules become fresh nodes with empty `task_ids`. History is lost on refactor.\n\nT0528 intentionally reserves a read-side hook for `.orbit/operations/<commit_sha>.json` but does not define the schema or the producer. This task produces the **design document** for that schema — the contract that agent edit paths will eventually emit against.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nThe long-term vision we aligned on: **Orbit owns symbol-level write operations**. Agents dispatched by Orbit call `graph.rename`, `graph.move`, `graph.split`, `graph.change_signature` etc. rather than raw file edits, and the commit carries an explicit operation log. Under that model:\n\n- Rename and move preserve identity *by fiat*, not by heuristic.\n- `task_ids` propagation is exact across any refactor Orbit itself performs.\n- Body-similarity heuristics stay dropped permanently — not because we chose lossy, but because we chose precise.\n\nThe identity matcher from T0528 remains the permanent reconciliation layer for **non-Orbit writes** (manual edits, upstream merges, external PRs). Operations enrich; they do not replace.\n\nBefore we can wire agents through any operation API, we need a concrete schema. This task delivers that design — on paper, not in code.\n\n## Deliverable\n\nA design document at `docs/design/graph-operations.md` covering:\n\n1. **Operation taxonomy** — the minimum set that actually preserves identity: `create`, `delete`, `rename`, `move`, `change_signature`, `change_body`, `split`, `merge`. Each operation's inputs and outputs. Whether it is compositional (e.g., is `move + rename` one `relocate` op or two ops?).\n2. **Canonical schema** — JSON Schema or equivalent for `.orbit/operations/<commit_sha>.json`. Top-level envelope (version, commit_sha, producer, operations array). Per-operation shape with required and optional fields.\n3. **Symbol addressing inside an operation** — how a `rename` operation names its subject. Current graph keys symbols by `(path, qualified_name, kind)` but rename/move changes exactly those fields. Propose either (a) a rebuild-issued node ID persisted on the node (graph-level stable ID), or (b) a pre-op address + post-op address pair. Pick one and defend it.\n4. **Validation rules** — when is an operation log well-formed? When is it valid against the commit's actual tree diff (e.g., a `rename` op claiming `Foo -> Bar` must match the tree: `Foo` gone, `Bar` added, bodies similar enough). Define the divergence policy — reject, warn, or prefer operation over tree.\n5. **Producer surface sketch** — the agent-facing API shape (`graph.rename(from, to)` etc.). One- or two-paragraph sketch per operation. Not a full API spec; enough to confirm the schema can be produced cleanly.\n6. **Backfill and migration** — what happens to commits from before the producer existed. Strategy: matcher-only on old commits, operation-log on new commits. No attempt to backfill operations.\n7. **Open questions** — flag what is not yet decided (e.g., language-agnostic addressing, multi-symbol atomic operations, how body-only refactors interact with `change_body` vs implicit diff).\n\n## Constraints / Notes\n\n- **Depends on T20260421-0528** — the read-side hook must exist first so the schema has a consumer waiting for it.\n- **Do not implement the producer** — this task is design only. No code. No agent API. No language-specific parsers. Those are separate, larger follow-ups.\n- **Do not implement the consumer beyond what T0528 already reserves** — if T0528's placeholder (`operations: []` array is valid) needs a versioning bump, propose it in the doc but do not land the code change here.\n- **Precedent to consider** — Unison's codebase model, refactoring-aware VCS literature. Cite if helpful.\n- **Audience** — implementing engineer/agent six months from now. The doc should be actionable as a spec, not exploratory.\n\n## Out of Scope\n\n- Any code changes.\n- Agent-facing API implementation.\n- Language-specific parser design (Rust-only vs polyglot is a doc-level discussion, not an implementation task).\n- Policy for operation-log signing, tamper resistance, or trust boundaries.\n- Performance analysis (premature; there is no producer to measure).",
    "execution_summary": "## Status\nsuccess\n\n## Summary of Changes\n- New prescriptive spec at `docs/design/knowledge-graph/specs/graph-operations.md` (~340 lines) covering all 7 task sections: 8-op taxonomy with inputs/outputs/compositionality, canonical JSON envelope + tagged-union per-op shape, stable-ID addressing (decision locked in), validation + divergence policy, producer API sketch per op, no-backfill migration policy, 5 open questions.\n- `ADR-010 — Orbit-owned symbol-level write operations` added to `docs/design/knowledge-graph/4_decisions.md` with `Proposed` status, cost line, and citation to T20260421-0543. Task References updated.\n- `Last updated` on `4_decisions.md` bumped to 2026-04-22.\n- No code changes. Consumer hook in `pipeline/attribute.rs` unchanged — the `{\"operations\":[]}` permissive skeleton from T20260421-0528 is a strict subset of this schema.\n\n## Strategic Decisions\n- Stable graph-level IDs (`node:<nanoid-21>` on `BaseNodeFields`) over pre/post address pairs. | Rationale: user confirmed stable IDs; alternative required an auxiliary correlation key that is a stable ID under a different name. Disambiguation under simultaneous axis changes stays simple; N-ary ops (split/merge) need named subject handles regardless.\n- Advisory-authoritative operations: accepted when consistent with tree diff, ignored with warning otherwise. | Rationale: the tree is ground truth; a producer bug must never silently rewrite history. Worst case is fallback to pre-producer matcher behavior.\n- Each op atomic per entry; compound refactors (move+rename) emit two entries referencing the same stable_id. | Rationale: per-entry tree-diff validation stays trivial; no compound primitive to overlap with atomic ones.\n- No retroactive operation logs. | Rationale: backfill would encode matcher lossiness as producer claims, strictly worse than leaving it as a best-guess.\n\n## Deviations from Original Plan\n- Spec path deviated from task spec (`docs/design/graph-operations.md`) to `docs/design/knowledge-graph/specs/graph-operations.md` per CONVENTIONS.md §2/§6. | Justification: graph operations are a mechanism of the knowledge graph; top-level design docs are forbidden outside feature folders. Filed friction T20260422-1559 tracking the path discrepancy for follow-up.\n- `Schema` presented as JSONC code blocks + prose rather than a literal JSON Schema file. | Justification: formal schema file (`operations-v1.json`) is explicitly deferred to the producer task when the consumer will actually parse it. Strict reading of AC #3 (\"JSON Schema or equivalent formal notation\") is satisfied by the equivalent-formal-notation interpretation; flagging in case reviewer prefers the stricter read.\n\n## Design Weaknesses / Risks\n- `stable_id` adds a new field to `BaseNodeFields`; requires a schema bump and one-time object-hash reallocation on first rebuild after the producer lands. | Severity: Medium | Mitigation: documented as cost in ADR-010; GC is already an open item (3_vision §1.10) so orphan accumulation doesn't raise new concerns.\n- `change_body` is optional — cannot distinguish \"producer intended\" from \"producer forgot\". | Severity: Low | Mitigation: Open Q3 in spec; mitigation proposed (require when producer non-null) but deferred pending producer data.\n- Spec commits to a per-entry atomicity model; a future higher-arity transactional op (Q2) would be additive. | Severity: Low | Mitigation: `schemaVersion` is monotonically increasing and the taxonomy is a tagged union — adding new ops does not break readers.\n- No signing/tamper resistance. | Severity: Low (scope excluded by task) | Mitigation: Open Q5 in spec.\n\n## Recommended Follow-Ups\n- Producer implementation task (the actual `orbit-engine` API + sidecar emission path). Flip ADR-010 to `Accepted` at that time.\n- Formal JSON Schema file (`crates/orbit-knowledge/src/pipeline/schemas/operations-v1.json`) — land with the producer.\n- Consumer strictening: upgrade `inspect_operation_log` to validate per-op shape and tree-diff consistency (currently permissive per §4 divergence policy). Land with the producer.\n- Resolve friction T20260422-1559 to stop future design-doc tasks from citing the wrong path.\n- Open Qs 1–5 are flagged in the spec; pick them up as discrete tasks if/when a multi-language producer or transactional-op need materializes.\n\n## Overall Assessment\nDesign is complete on paper and ready for review. No code churn, no backwards-compat risk. Stable-ID + advisory-authoritative combo gives Orbit precise attribution for refactors it performs while keeping the matcher as the reconciliation layer for everything else. Every load-bearing decision has an explicit rationale and a named cost. Five open questions bracket what is deliberately unresolved.\n",
